+{"_type":"issue","id":"mindspec-wpf0","title":"Enforce the panel gate inside `mindspec complete` (declared bead ID) instead of a shell-parsing PreToolUse hook — retire the heuristic matcher","description":"ZFC + fail-open concern raised 2026-06-14 (Max). The pre-complete panel gate (ADR-0037) is currently enforced by a PreToolUse hook (internal/hook/precomplete.go) that HEURISTICALLY parses the raw shell command to detect 'mindspec complete \u003cid\u003e': strippedCompleteFields tokenizes the string and strips env-assignments + cd/pushd + env/timeout/xargs/command wrappers, then matches the terminal isMindspecBinary+fields[1]=='complete' and completeBeadID extracts the id from fields[2:].\n\nPROBLEM: this is non-ZFC (guessing intent from a free-form string when no declared signal exists at the hook boundary) and structurally FAIL-OPEN — quoted forms (sh -c '... complete' / eval '...') are unreachable by a non-executing tokenizer (accepted residual per ADR-0037 §6), and unhandled wrappers (nice/nohup/sudo, novel forms) silently slip the gate. Spec 098 R4 (7eup) extended the matcher to catch more wrappers + fixed completeBeadID to actually extract the id, but that ADDS heuristic surface rather than removing it.\n\nZFC-CLEAN FIX: enforce the gate INSIDE 'mindspec complete' at the start of its own execution, where the bead ID is a DECLARED argument (no shell parsing, no wrapper-stripping, no fail-open residual). The command knows exactly which bead it is completing, reads panel.json + reviewed_head_sha (ADR-0037), and blocks with the ADR-0035 block-message protocol if the threshold isn't met — every invocation form (wrapped, quoted, aliased) is covered for free.\n\nSCOPE/DECISIONS: (a) keep the PreToolUse hook as a defense-in-depth backstop, or remove it once the in-binary check lands? (b) the in-binary check must read the same panel.json convention + thresholds + reviewed-HEAD freshness as the hook; (c) honor the fail-open-without-a-panel / fail-closed-with-one rule (ADR-0037 §6) from inside complete; (d) once in-binary enforcement is authoritative, RETIRE/shrink segmentInvokesComplete/strippedCompleteFields/completeBeadID to reduce the heuristic. Related: ADR-0037 (panel gate contract), ADR-0036 (ZFC), closed mindspec-7eup, spec 098 R4.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"feature","owner":"richardmaxsteel@gmail.com","created_at":"2026-06-14T12:46:20Z","created_by":"mrmaxsteel","updated_at":"2026-06-14T12:46:20Z","dependencies":[{"issue_id":"mindspec-wpf0","depends_on_id":"mindspec-7eup","type":"discovered-from","created_at":"2026-06-14T13:46:20Z","created_by":"mrmaxsteel","metadata":"{}"}],"dependency_count":0,"dependent_count":0,"comment_count":0}
+{"_type":"issue","id":"mindspec-uopd","title":"[098 follow-up] mindspec-098-bd-committed-read: complete close-verify needs a committed-state read distinct from bd show (the deeper 2u0u)","description":"Spec 098 R2 forces bd dolt commit + re-verifies, but bd exposes NO committed-state read distinct from bd show (probe: dolt.auto-commit=on, bd dolt status reports engine not working-set). The observed 2u0u (complete reports closed+exit0, a FRESH bd show later shows in_progress) is therefore NOT caught by the same-session re-read — likely a dolt session/connection/worktree isolation issue. Needs either a bd capability to read committed state distinct from the session, or an upstream-bd fix. Until then, complete still requires the manual bd close workaround on the rare miss.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"richardmaxsteel@gmail.com","created_at":"2026-06-14T08:05:18Z","created_by":"mrmaxsteel","updated_at":"2026-06-14T08:05:18Z","dependencies":[{"issue_id":"mindspec-uopd","depends_on_id":"mindspec-9n2h","type":"discovered-from","created_at":"2026-06-14T09:05:17Z","created_by":"mrmaxsteel","metadata":"{}"}],"dependency_count":0,"dependent_count":0,"comment_count":0}
 {"_type":"issue","id":"mindspec-dn4h.5","title":"[098-lifecycle-correctness-2] Bead 5: Make the harness merge-to-main assertion direction-aware (R5 / pi24)","description":"`preApproveImplMainMergeOrPRViolation` (`internal/harness/asserts.go` ~199-207) flags ANY `git merge`\nwhose args contain both `merge` and `main` as a pre-approve \"merge-to-main occurred\" violation,\nregardless of DIRECTION — so the legitimate `git merge main` (merging main INTO a feature/spec\nbranch) matches the same as the genuinely-bad `git merge \u003cspec-branch\u003e` while on `main`, and the\nmessage is misleading for the safe direction. The agent-facing root cause was already fixed in\n`d5d8ee54`/`implement.md:98`; this is the residual test-layer defect. Make the assertion\ndirection-aware — flag ONLY a merge that LANDS content onto `main` (run while the checkout is on\n`main` / `git merge \u003cspec-branch\u003e` into main), allow `git merge main` into another branch — and\ncorrect the violation message. Single-file (`asserts.go`); independent of all other beads (Bead 1\nalso lives under `internal/harness` but in `scenario_spec_lifecycle.go` — different file, no\nserialization; whichever lands SECOND re-runs `go test ./internal/harness/...`). (S.)\n\n**Steps**\n1. In `preApproveImplMainMergeOrPRViolation` (`internal/harness/asserts.go` ~199-207), replace the\n   direction-blind `containsAll(args,\"merge\") \u0026\u0026 containsAll(args,\"main\")` condition with a\n   DIRECTION-aware one that flags only a merge LANDING ONTO `main`. The bad direction is identified\n   by the merge OPERAND being a spec/feature branch (e.g. `spec/` / a non-`main` ref) — i.e.\n   distinguish `git merge main` (operand == `main`, the SAFE update INTO a branch) from\n   `git merge spec/\u003cid\u003e` (operand is the spec branch, landing onto main). Keep the existing\n   `isCanonicalInternal` allow-list (the approve-impl `--no-ff spec/\u003cid\u003e … into main` pattern)\n   untouched.\n2. Correct the violation message to describe the ACTUAL bad direction (a merge landing content onto\n   `main` before approve-impl), not the misleading \"merge-to-main occurred\" wording that also fired\n   on the safe `git merge main`.\n3. UPDATE the message-substring assertion in the existing `TestAssertNoPreApproveImplMainMergeOrPR`\n   (`internal/harness/scenario_test.go:596`), which asserts the violation error\n   `strings.Contains(... , \"merge-to-main occurred before approve impl\")`. Since step 2 corrects the\n   violation message to describe the actual bad direction, this substring assertion changes — point it\n   at the corrected message text so the existing \"rejects merge spec into main before approve impl\"\n   sub-test still passes (its bad-direction event stream — `git merge --no-ff spec/001-test main` —\n   must remain flagged). Within-bead test edit.\n4. Add a test in `internal/harness/` covering BOTH directions: a `git merge main` (into a\n   feature/spec branch) is NOT flagged; a genuinely-bad merge landing onto `main` (the\n   non-canonical, non-`main`-operand direction) before approve-impl IS still flagged with the\n   corrected message. (Re-run `go test ./internal/harness/...` whole-package since Bead 1 shares the\n   package — whichever lands second re-runs it.)\n\n**Verification**\n- [ ] `go test ./internal/harness/...` — the assertion no longer flags `git merge main` (safe\n      direction into a branch); still flags the bad direction (a merge landing onto `main`)\n- [ ] The `isCanonicalInternal` approve-impl allow-list is preserved; the violation message describes\n      the actual bad direction\n- [ ] RED-on-revert: restoring the direction-blind check makes the `git merge main` (safe) test row\n      fail (false positive); golangci-lint clean\n\n**Acceptance Criteria**\n- [ ] `preApproveImplMainMergeOrPRViolation` flags only merges landing onto `main` before\n      approve-impl (with an accurate message) and no longer flags a legitimate `git merge main` into\n      a feature/spec branch. A test covers both directions. RED-on-revert.\n\n**Depends on**\nNone","design":"## Requirements\n\n1. **(myn3 — M) Wire ADR/ownership coverage into the fixture-based LLM-harness impl-approve scenario (`ScenarioImplApprove`) so a clean impl-approve succeeds.** Failure mode today: `ScenarioImplApprove` (`internal/harness/scenario_spec_lifecycle.go`, the builder around lines 360-444) commits a source `done.go` at the sandbox root (written to `wt.SpecWtDir+\"/done.go\"`, landing as `done.go` on `main` after merge) but ships NO `.mindspec/docs/domains/*/OWNERSHIP.yaml` coverage and leaves the fixture plan's `adr_citations` empty. `CheckADRDivergence` runs unconditionally in impl-approve (`internal/approve/impl.go:277`) and, absent `--override-adr`/`--supersede-adr`, returns a hard error when `adrResult.HasFailures()` (`internal/approve/impl.go:302-305`) — so the committed-but-unowned `done.go` triggers `adr-divergence-unowned` and a perfectly clean approve exits 1. The shared helper `writeSandboxDomainCoverage` (`internal/harness/scenario_contract_hardening.go:61`) already produces the minimal ownership + Accepted-ADR-0001 + plan-`adr_citations` triple and is wired into 6 other scenarios (stale_phase, gate_discovery, etc.) but is NOT applied to this legacy scenario. Change: apply the proven recipe to `ScenarioImplApprove` — call `writeSandboxDomainCoverage(sandbox, \"done.go\")` and `sandbox.Commit(...)` at the sandbox ROOT BEFORE `setupWorktrees` forks the worktree (so the OWNERSHIP.yaml + Accepted ADR-0001 are present on the base ref the divergence gate diffs against), with the path claim (`done.go`) matching where the impl file lands on `main` after merge, and add `adr_citations:\\n- ADR-0001` to the fixture plan's frontmatter (currently absent at the inline plan around lines 386-395). **What must be true after:** `ScenarioImplApprove` passes with a clean impl-approve (exit 0, spec branch merged + deleted, worktree removed, impl content on main) and NO spurious `adr-divergence-unowned` block.\n\n   1a. **(DEFERRED — follow-up bead) `ScenarioSpecToIdle` is NOT in scope for this requirement.** `ScenarioSpecToIdle` (`internal/harness/scenario_spec_lifecycle.go:10-56`) has an EMPTY `Setup` and is FULLY agent-authored: the haiku agent picks the impl filename (`hello.go`), runs the whole lifecycle live, and authors `spec.md`/`plan.md` itself. The fixture therefore cannot pre-inject `adr_citations` into the agent-generated plan. Even though ownership path-matching DOES support globs (`internal/validate/ownership.go` `GlobMatch`, so a wildcard claim could cover an agent-chosen filename), `attributeDomain` + the `adr-divergence-uncovered` branch require the covering ADR to be **plan-CITED** (`IsDomainCovered`, `internal/validate/plan.go:577`) — and a fixture cannot cite an ADR in a plan the agent writes, nor is the agent prompted to. So a Setup-committed wildcard ownership claim would merely flip the failure from `adr-divergence-unowned` to `adr-divergence-uncovered`, not make the clean approve pass. Because no fixture-only mechanism makes `ScenarioSpecToIdle`'s agent-authored impl-approve pass cleanly, it is DEFERRED to a named follow-up bead (`mindspec-098-spectoidle-coverage`, to be filed at spec-approve) which will solve the distinct agent-prompting problem (prompt the agent to author the ownership + ADR-citation coverage triple, or relax the harness assertion for this agent-driven scenario). This spec's Req 1 / AC-1 scope to `ScenarioImplApprove` only.\n\n2. **(9n2h — M) Harden `complete` close-verify so a non-persisting `bd close` is reliably DETECTED via a forced commit + committed-state verification, never silently completed.** Failure mode today: after `closeBeadFn` returns nil, `complete` re-reads status via `fetchBeadByIDFn` → `next.FetchBeadByID` → `bd show --json` (`internal/next/beads.go:172`) — the SAME bd/Dolt session path the close wrote through, with no forced commit and no committed-state read. The post-close retry loop (`internal/complete/complete.go:401-409`) retries only on a read ERROR; it never confirms DURABILITY, so a close that lands in-session but does not persist to committed Dolt state reads back `\"closed\"` (case (a) at `complete.go:432`) and `complete` proceeds to merge + worktree removal on an unverified close. (Observed recurring this session; the `default` case (b) at `complete.go:435` already hard-errors when the re-read shows open/in_progress, but does not catch the in-session-only \"reads closed\" case.) Note: the missing boundary is NOT process separation — the re-read is already a second `bd` subprocess. The missing boundary is an independent COMMITTED-state verification.\n\n   **Change (concrete, testable durability mechanism):** after `closeBeadFn` returns nil, force durability with `bd dolt commit` — the strongest available bd durability primitive, confirmed present via `bd dolt commit --help` (\"Create a Dolt commit from any uncommitted changes in the working set … useful before push operations that require a clean working set\"). Add a new `internal/bead` wrapper (`bdcli.go`, e.g. `DoltCommit()`, running `bd dolt commit`) per ADR-0012 rather than ad-hoc shelling. Then perform a committed-state verification re-read. If EITHER the `bd dolt commit` step FAILS or the verification read shows the bead is not `closed`/errors, emit a clear, recoverable ADR-0035 error (via the existing `guard.NewFailure` recovery-line path) that KEEPS the worktree, does NOT set `BeadClosed`, and is safe to re-run (both the close step and `bd dolt commit` are idempotent) — mirroring the existing case-(b) PRE-MERGE return at `complete.go:435-444`. The command must NEVER print `closed` + exit 0 on an unverified close.\n\n   **Injectable test seam (required):** add a new function-variable seam alongside the existing `closeBeadFn` / `fetchBeadByIDFn` package-level seams (`internal/complete/complete.go:28,34`) for the durability/verification step — e.g. `doltCommitFn = bead.DoltCommit` and a `verifyCommittedFn` (the committed-state verifier) — so a RED-on-revert regression test can simulate the make-or-break case: `closeBeadFn` returns nil, the normal `fetchBeadByIDFn` returns `\"closed\"`, but the committed-state verifier (`verifyCommittedFn`) reports not-closed/error → assert a non-zero error, the worktree is RETAINED, and `BeadClosed == false`. This is the exact failure today's seams cannot simulate (today they can only re-read open/error), so the new seam is what makes the bug testable.\n\n   **HONESTY CLAUSE (implementation fallback, stated up front so R2 is shippable either way):** if implementation finds that `bd` exposes NO committed-state read distinct from `bd show` (i.e. after `bd dolt commit`, `bd show` still reads the same session state and a genuinely-in-session-only close still reads `\"closed\"`), then `verifyCommittedFn` cannot be grounded as a true committed-vs-session discriminator. In that case R2 is scoped to: (a) force `bd dolt commit` after every close, (b) DETECT and error on `bd dolt commit` FAILURE (non-zero exit / wrapper error) — never silently proceed on an unverified close, (c) emit the recoverable ADR-0035 error keeping the worktree / `BeadClosed=false`, and (d) FILE an upstream-bd bead (`mindspec-098-bd-committed-read`) for the residual durability-read gap. Under this fallback the RED test asserts the `bd dolt commit`-failure path (`doltCommitFn` returns an error → recoverable error, retained worktree, `BeadClosed == false`). Either path is implementable, testable RED-on-revert, and shippable. **What must be true after:** after `bd close`, `complete` forces `bd dolt commit` and (where a committed-state read exists) verifies the committed status; a close whose durability cannot be confirmed — commit failure OR a committed-state mismatch — is detected and surfaced as a clear recoverable ADR-0035 error with the worktree retained and `BeadClosed` unset; `complete` never prints `closed` + exit 0 on an unverified close.\n\n3. **(e6qq — S) Relax the plan-approve `version` gate by AUTO-FILLING a canonical default of `\"1\"`.** Failure mode + behavior change (this requirement LOOSENS a gate): `internal/validate/plan.go:304` raises a HARD error `frontmatter-version: missing required field: version` when `fm.Version == \"\"`, with no auto-default-fill — even though sibling checks were already relaxed for ZFC alignment (`StepsCount \u003c 3` demoted to a warning at `plan.go:797`; empty `adr_citations` demoted to a warning when a `## ADR Fitness` section is present at `plan.go:137-147`). An agent-generated plan that is otherwise valid but omits only `version` is hard-blocked on a field that can be deterministically defaulted, and nothing downstream reads `PlanFrontmatter.Version` (verified: the only consumers — `internal/approve/plan.go`, `internal/validate/divergence.go` — read `ADRCitations`/`WorkChunks` only), so any well-defined default is safe. Change (ONE pinned behavior): when `fm.Version == \"\"`, AUTO-FILL it to the canonical default `version` value `\"1\"` (the string `\"1\"`) instead of raising `frontmatter-version`, so the plan validates. Auto-fill is preferred over demote-to-warning because it makes agent plans Just Work. **What must be true after:** a plan missing only `version` (all other required fields present) no longer fails `mindspec validate plan` / `approve plan`; the `version` field is treated as / written with the exact value `\"1\"`. (This is an intentional gate loosening; `status` and `spec_id` remain hard-required.)\n\n4. **(7eup — S) Make the pre-complete gate matcher catch unquoted wrapper-prefixed `mindspec complete`.** Failure mode + behavior change (this requirement TIGHTENS a gate): `segmentInvokesComplete` (`internal/hook/precomplete.go:366-394`) strips only leading env-assignments (`isEnvAssignment`) and `cd`/`pushd` prefixes before checking `fields[0]` is the mindspec binary and `fields[1] == \"complete\"`. Unquoted wrapper commands therefore fail OPEN: `env VAR=x mindspec complete …`, `timeout 30 mindspec complete …`, `xargs … mindspec complete`, and `command mindspec complete …` are not recognized as invoking complete, so the pre-complete gate does not fire. Change: extend the matcher to recognize and skip the catchable unquoted wrapper prefixes (`env`, `timeout`, `xargs`, `command`) so the wrapped `mindspec complete` is still detected. The matcher's terminal check is PRESERVED unchanged — after stripping wrapper prefixes it still requires `isMindspecBinary(fields[0]) \u0026\u0026 fields[1] == \"complete\"`, so the tightening fires ONLY when `complete` is genuinely the wrapped command and introduces no false positives (`timeout 30 go test` strips to `go test` → not mindspec → false; `env FOO=bar mindspec next` → `fields[1] != \"complete\"` → false). The exact per-wrapper arg-skip rules (`timeout`: skip the duration plus its `-s SIG`/`--preserve-status`/`-k` flags; `command`: skip `-p`/`-v`/`-V`; `xargs`: skip its flags; bare `env`: skip leading `VAR=x` assignments after the keyword) are a plan-phase implementation detail to enumerate precisely so the matcher neither under-skips (misses the wrapped complete) nor over-skips into a wrong `fields[0]`. The QUOTED `sh -c '…'` / `eval '…'` forms are structurally unreachable by a non-executing tokenizer and remain an explicitly-documented accepted ADR-0037 residual — do NOT attempt to match them; document that boundary in code/comment. **What must be true after:** `env VAR=x mindspec complete`, `timeout 30 mindspec complete`, `xargs … mindspec complete`, and `command mindspec complete` are all detected by `segmentInvokesComplete` and trigger the pre-complete gate; the quoted `sh -c`/`eval` forms remain a documented residual.\n\n5. **(pi24 — S) Make the harness merge-to-main assertion direction-aware and fix its message.** Failure mode today (test-layer only): `preApproveImplMainMergeOrPRViolation` (`internal/harness/asserts.go`, the merge check around lines 199-207) flags any `git merge` whose args contain both `merge` and `main` as a pre-approve \"merge-to-main occurred before approve impl\" violation, regardless of DIRECTION. This is direction-blind: `git merge main` (merging main INTO a feature/spec branch — a legitimate update) matches the same as the genuinely-bad `git merge \u003cbranch\u003e` while on `main`, and the message (\"merge-to-main occurred\") is misleading for the safe direction. (The agent-facing root cause was already fixed in commit `d5d8ee54` / `implement.md:98`; this is the residual test-layer defect.) Change: make the assertion direction-aware — only flag the genuinely-bad direction (a merge that lands content ONTO `main`, i.e. run while the checkout is on `main` / `git merge \u003cspec-branch\u003e` into main), allowing `git merge main` into another branch — and correct the violation message to describe the actual bad direction. **What must be true after:** the assertion flags only merges that land onto `main` before approve-impl (with an accurate message) and no longer flags a legitimate `git merge main` into a feature/spec branch.\n\n## ADR Decisions\n\nCited by ID — full text under `.mindspec/docs/adr/`:\n\n- see ADR-0035 — Agent Error Contract — Recovery Lines and Exit Codes\n- see ADR-0037 — Panel Gate as Enforced Contract — panel.json Convention, Thresholds, and the Trust Boundary\n- see ADR-0036 — Ownership Discovery — Zero Framework Cognition for OWNERSHIP.yaml and source_globs\n- see ADR-0012 — Compose with External CLIs, Don't Wrap Them","acceptance_criteria":"- [ ] `preApproveImplMainMergeOrPRViolation` flags only merges landing onto `main` before\napprove-impl (with an accurate message) and no longer flags a legitimate `git merge main` into\na feature/spec branch. A test covers both directions. RED-on-revert.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","assignee":"mrmaxsteel","owner":"richardmaxsteel@gmail.com","created_at":"2026-06-13T22:28:02Z","created_by":"mrmaxsteel","updated_at":"2026-06-14T06:50:37Z","started_at":"2026-06-13T22:29:20Z","closed_at":"2026-06-14T06:50:37Z","close_reason":"merge landed but close did not persist (2u0u); manual","metadata":{"spec_id":"098-lifecycle-correctness-2","file_paths":null,"mindspec_doc_skew_at":"2026-06-14T06:50:08Z","mindspec_doc_skew_by":"richardmaxsteel@gmail.com","mindspec_doc_skew_reason":"Test-layer harness fix (R5/pi24): make preApproveImplMainMergeOrPRViolation direction-aware — a safe 'git merge main' (pulling main into a feature/bead branch) is no longer flagged; only non-main non-canonical merges are. internal/harness (execution-owned, ADR-0035/0037) test-assertion change, no production behavior change. 1-reviewer verify APPROVE; RED-on-revert pinned."},"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"mindspec-dn4h.5","depends_on_id":"mindspec-dn4h","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-06-13T23:28:02Z","created_by":"mrmaxsteel","metadata":"{}"}],"dependency_count":0,"dependent_count":0,"comment_count":0}
 {"_type":"issue","id":"mindspec-dn4h.4","title":"[098-lifecycle-correctness-2] Bead 4: Catch unquoted wrapper-prefixed `mindspec complete` in the pre-complete matcher (R4 / 7eup)","description":"`segmentInvokesComplete` (`internal/hook/precomplete.go:366-394`) strips only leading env-assignments\nand `cd`/`pushd` prefixes before checking `isMindspecBinary(fields[0]) \u0026\u0026 fields[1] == \"complete\"`, so\nunquoted wrapper commands fail OPEN: `env VAR=x mindspec complete`, `timeout 30 mindspec complete`,\n`xargs … mindspec complete`, and `command mindspec complete` are not detected. This requirement\nTIGHTENS the gate: extend the prefix-stripping loop to skip the four catchable unquoted wrappers\n(`env`, `timeout`, `xargs`, `command`) with correct per-wrapper arg/flag skipping, while PRESERVING\nthe terminal `isMindspecBinary + fields[1]=='complete'` check unchanged so the tightening fires ONLY\nwhen `complete` is genuinely the wrapped command (no false positives). The QUOTED `sh -c '…'` /\n`eval '…'` forms stay a documented accepted ADR-0037 residual (in-code comment). Single-file,\nindependent of all other beads. (S.)\n\n**Steps**\n1. In the prefix-stripping `for` loop in `segmentInvokesComplete` (`precomplete.go:368-385`), add\n   cases for the four unquoted wrappers AFTER the existing `isEnvAssignment` / `cd`/`pushd` cases,\n   each consuming exactly its wrapper token plus its own args so the loop continues at the wrapped\n   command:\n   - `env`: skip the bare `env` keyword, then skip any leading `VAR=val` assignments (reuse\n     `isEnvAssignment`) — `env FOO=bar mindspec complete` → `mindspec complete`. NOTE: the existing\n     stripper ALREADY consumes the `VAR=val` form (via `isEnvAssignment`); the genuinely-NEW token\n     this case adds is the BARE `env` keyword (the `env` literal itself, not an assignment).\n   - `timeout`: skip `timeout`, skip its optional flags (`-s SIG`/`--signal=…`, `-k DURATION`/\n     `--kill-after=…`, `--preserve-status`, `--foreground`), then skip EXACTLY ONE non-flag operand —\n     the mandatory DURATION — before the loop returns to the terminal check —\n     `timeout 30 mindspec complete` → `mindspec complete`; `timeout -s KILL 30 …` handled.\n   - `command`: skip `command`, skip its `-p`/`-v`/`-V` flags — `command mindspec complete` →\n     `mindspec complete`.\n   - `xargs`: skip `xargs` and its flags (e.g. `-n`/`-I`/`-0`/`-P` with their operands) up to the\n     command token, consuming EXACTLY ONE non-flag operand (the command being run) before the\n     terminal check — `xargs … mindspec complete` → `mindspec complete`.\n   PIN the rule that the `timeout`/`xargs` skip consumes EXACTLY ONE non-flag operand (the\n   duration/command) before returning to the terminal `isMindspecBinary(fields[0])` check — NOT a\n   greedy run of operands — so the matcher neither UNDER-skips (misses the wrapped complete) NOR\n   OVER-skips past the wrapped command onto a wrong `fields[0]` (e.g. consuming `mindspec` itself and\n   landing on `complete`).\n2. PRESERVE the terminal check unchanged: after stripping, still require\n   `len(fields) \u003e= 2 \u0026\u0026 isMindspecBinary(fields[0]) \u0026\u0026 fields[1] == \"complete\"`. This keeps the\n   negatives FALSE: `timeout 30 go test` → `go test` → not mindspec → false;\n   `env FOO=bar mindspec next` → `fields[1] != \"complete\"` → false.\n3. Add an in-code comment documenting that the QUOTED `sh -c '…'` / `eval '…'` wrapper forms are an\n   explicitly-accepted ADR-0037 residual (a non-executing tokenizer structurally cannot reach them)\n   and are deliberately NOT matched.\n4. EXTEND the existing table test `TestMatchMindspecComplete`\n   (`internal/hook/precomplete_match_test.go`, the table at ~line 20 already exercising\n   `matchMindspecComplete` → `segmentInvokesComplete` with env-prefix/cd-prefix rows) — do NOT create\n   a new `precomplete_test.go` file. Add rows: each unquoted wrapper form around `mindspec complete`\n   (`env VAR=x …`, bare `env mindspec complete`, `timeout 30 …`, `timeout -s KILL 30 …`, `xargs … …`,\n   `command …`) returns TRUE; the negatives (`timeout 30 go test`, `env FOO=bar mindspec next`,\n   bare `go test`) return FALSE. Include a row pinning that the `timeout`/`xargs` single-operand skip\n   does NOT over-skip (e.g. `timeout 30 mindspec complete X` matches — the matcher lands on\n   `mindspec`/`complete`, not on `complete`/`X`).\n\n**Verification**\n- [ ] `go test ./internal/hook/...` — `segmentInvokesComplete` returns TRUE for each unquoted wrapper\n      form around `mindspec complete` and FALSE for `timeout 30 go test` / `env FOO=bar mindspec next`\n- [ ] The terminal `isMindspecBinary + fields[1]=='complete'` check is unchanged (no false positives)\n- [ ] The quoted `sh -c`/`eval` residual is documented in an in-code comment (ADR-0037)\n- [ ] RED-on-revert: reverting the wrapper cases makes the wrapper-true table rows fail; golangci-lint clean\n\n**Acceptance Criteria**\n- [ ] `segmentInvokesComplete` returns true for `env VAR=x mindspec complete`,\n      `timeout 30 mindspec complete`, `xargs … mindspec complete`, and `command mindspec complete`;\n      `timeout 30 go test` and `env FOO=bar mindspec next` are NOT caught; the quoted `sh -c`/`eval`\n      residual is documented. Table-driven tests cover the wrapper prefixes. RED-on-revert.\n\n**Depends on**\nNone","design":"## Requirements\n\n1. **(myn3 — M) Wire ADR/ownership coverage into the fixture-based LLM-harness impl-approve scenario (`ScenarioImplApprove`) so a clean impl-approve succeeds.** Failure mode today: `ScenarioImplApprove` (`internal/harness/scenario_spec_lifecycle.go`, the builder around lines 360-444) commits a source `done.go` at the sandbox root (written to `wt.SpecWtDir+\"/done.go\"`, landing as `done.go` on `main` after merge) but ships NO `.mindspec/docs/domains/*/OWNERSHIP.yaml` coverage and leaves the fixture plan's `adr_citations` empty. `CheckADRDivergence` runs unconditionally in impl-approve (`internal/approve/impl.go:277`) and, absent `--override-adr`/`--supersede-adr`, returns a hard error when `adrResult.HasFailures()` (`internal/approve/impl.go:302-305`) — so the committed-but-unowned `done.go` triggers `adr-divergence-unowned` and a perfectly clean approve exits 1. The shared helper `writeSandboxDomainCoverage` (`internal/harness/scenario_contract_hardening.go:61`) already produces the minimal ownership + Accepted-ADR-0001 + plan-`adr_citations` triple and is wired into 6 other scenarios (stale_phase, gate_discovery, etc.) but is NOT applied to this legacy scenario. Change: apply the proven recipe to `ScenarioImplApprove` — call `writeSandboxDomainCoverage(sandbox, \"done.go\")` and `sandbox.Commit(...)` at the sandbox ROOT BEFORE `setupWorktrees` forks the worktree (so the OWNERSHIP.yaml + Accepted ADR-0001 are present on the base ref the divergence gate diffs against), with the path claim (`done.go`) matching where the impl file lands on `main` after merge, and add `adr_citations:\\n- ADR-0001` to the fixture plan's frontmatter (currently absent at the inline plan around lines 386-395). **What must be true after:** `ScenarioImplApprove` passes with a clean impl-approve (exit 0, spec branch merged + deleted, worktree removed, impl content on main) and NO spurious `adr-divergence-unowned` block.\n\n   1a. **(DEFERRED — follow-up bead) `ScenarioSpecToIdle` is NOT in scope for this requirement.** `ScenarioSpecToIdle` (`internal/harness/scenario_spec_lifecycle.go:10-56`) has an EMPTY `Setup` and is FULLY agent-authored: the haiku agent picks the impl filename (`hello.go`), runs the whole lifecycle live, and authors `spec.md`/`plan.md` itself. The fixture therefore cannot pre-inject `adr_citations` into the agent-generated plan. Even though ownership path-matching DOES support globs (`internal/validate/ownership.go` `GlobMatch`, so a wildcard claim could cover an agent-chosen filename), `attributeDomain` + the `adr-divergence-uncovered` branch require the covering ADR to be **plan-CITED** (`IsDomainCovered`, `internal/validate/plan.go:577`) — and a fixture cannot cite an ADR in a plan the agent writes, nor is the agent prompted to. So a Setup-committed wildcard ownership claim would merely flip the failure from `adr-divergence-unowned` to `adr-divergence-uncovered`, not make the clean approve pass. Because no fixture-only mechanism makes `ScenarioSpecToIdle`'s agent-authored impl-approve pass cleanly, it is DEFERRED to a named follow-up bead (`mindspec-098-spectoidle-coverage`, to be filed at spec-approve) which will solve the distinct agent-prompting problem (prompt the agent to author the ownership + ADR-citation coverage triple, or relax the harness assertion for this agent-driven scenario). This spec's Req 1 / AC-1 scope to `ScenarioImplApprove` only.\n\n2. **(9n2h — M) Harden `complete` close-verify so a non-persisting `bd close` is reliably DETECTED via a forced commit + committed-state verification, never silently completed.** Failure mode today: after `closeBeadFn` returns nil, `complete` re-reads status via `fetchBeadByIDFn` → `next.FetchBeadByID` → `bd show --json` (`internal/next/beads.go:172`) — the SAME bd/Dolt session path the close wrote through, with no forced commit and no committed-state read. The post-close retry loop (`internal/complete/complete.go:401-409`) retries only on a read ERROR; it never confirms DURABILITY, so a close that lands in-session but does not persist to committed Dolt state reads back `\"closed\"` (case (a) at `complete.go:432`) and `complete` proceeds to merge + worktree removal on an unverified close. (Observed recurring this session; the `default` case (b) at `complete.go:435` already hard-errors when the re-read shows open/in_progress, but does not catch the in-session-only \"reads closed\" case.) Note: the missing boundary is NOT process separation — the re-read is already a second `bd` subprocess. The missing boundary is an independent COMMITTED-state verification.\n\n   **Change (concrete, testable durability mechanism):** after `closeBeadFn` returns nil, force durability with `bd dolt commit` — the strongest available bd durability primitive, confirmed present via `bd dolt commit --help` (\"Create a Dolt commit from any uncommitted changes in the working set … useful before push operations that require a clean working set\"). Add a new `internal/bead` wrapper (`bdcli.go`, e.g. `DoltCommit()`, running `bd dolt commit`) per ADR-0012 rather than ad-hoc shelling. Then perform a committed-state verification re-read. If EITHER the `bd dolt commit` step FAILS or the verification read shows the bead is not `closed`/errors, emit a clear, recoverable ADR-0035 error (via the existing `guard.NewFailure` recovery-line path) that KEEPS the worktree, does NOT set `BeadClosed`, and is safe to re-run (both the close step and `bd dolt commit` are idempotent) — mirroring the existing case-(b) PRE-MERGE return at `complete.go:435-444`. The command must NEVER print `closed` + exit 0 on an unverified close.\n\n   **Injectable test seam (required):** add a new function-variable seam alongside the existing `closeBeadFn` / `fetchBeadByIDFn` package-level seams (`internal/complete/complete.go:28,34`) for the durability/verification step — e.g. `doltCommitFn = bead.DoltCommit` and a `verifyCommittedFn` (the committed-state verifier) — so a RED-on-revert regression test can simulate the make-or-break case: `closeBeadFn` returns nil, the normal `fetchBeadByIDFn` returns `\"closed\"`, but the committed-state verifier (`verifyCommittedFn`) reports not-closed/error → assert a non-zero error, the worktree is RETAINED, and `BeadClosed == false`. This is the exact failure today's seams cannot simulate (today they can only re-read open/error), so the new seam is what makes the bug testable.\n\n   **HONESTY CLAUSE (implementation fallback, stated up front so R2 is shippable either way):** if implementation finds that `bd` exposes NO committed-state read distinct from `bd show` (i.e. after `bd dolt commit`, `bd show` still reads the same session state and a genuinely-in-session-only close still reads `\"closed\"`), then `verifyCommittedFn` cannot be grounded as a true committed-vs-session discriminator. In that case R2 is scoped to: (a) force `bd dolt commit` after every close, (b) DETECT and error on `bd dolt commit` FAILURE (non-zero exit / wrapper error) — never silently proceed on an unverified close, (c) emit the recoverable ADR-0035 error keeping the worktree / `BeadClosed=false`, and (d) FILE an upstream-bd bead (`mindspec-098-bd-committed-read`) for the residual durability-read gap. Under this fallback the RED test asserts the `bd dolt commit`-failure path (`doltCommitFn` returns an error → recoverable error, retained worktree, `BeadClosed == false`). Either path is implementable, testable RED-on-revert, and shippable. **What must be true after:** after `bd close`, `complete` forces `bd dolt commit` and (where a committed-state read exists) verifies the committed status; a close whose durability cannot be confirmed — commit failure OR a committed-state mismatch — is detected and surfaced as a clear recoverable ADR-0035 error with the worktree retained and `BeadClosed` unset; `complete` never prints `closed` + exit 0 on an unverified close.\n\n3. **(e6qq — S) Relax the plan-approve `version` gate by AUTO-FILLING a canonical default of `\"1\"`.** Failure mode + behavior change (this requirement LOOSENS a gate): `internal/validate/plan.go:304` raises a HARD error `frontmatter-version: missing required field: version` when `fm.Version == \"\"`, with no auto-default-fill — even though sibling checks were already relaxed for ZFC alignment (`StepsCount \u003c 3` demoted to a warning at `plan.go:797`; empty `adr_citations` demoted to a warning when a `## ADR Fitness` section is present at `plan.go:137-147`). An agent-generated plan that is otherwise valid but omits only `version` is hard-blocked on a field that can be deterministically defaulted, and nothing downstream reads `PlanFrontmatter.Version` (verified: the only consumers — `internal/approve/plan.go`, `internal/validate/divergence.go` — read `ADRCitations`/`WorkChunks` only), so any well-defined default is safe. Change (ONE pinned behavior): when `fm.Version == \"\"`, AUTO-FILL it to the canonical default `version` value `\"1\"` (the string `\"1\"`) instead of raising `frontmatter-version`, so the plan validates. Auto-fill is preferred over demote-to-warning because it makes agent plans Just Work. **What must be true after:** a plan missing only `version` (all other required fields present) no longer fails `mindspec validate plan` / `approve plan`; the `version` field is treated as / written with the exact value `\"1\"`. (This is an intentional gate loosening; `status` and `spec_id` remain hard-required.)\n\n4. **(7eup — S) Make the pre-complete gate matcher catch unquoted wrapper-prefixed `mindspec complete`.** Failure mode + behavior change (this requirement TIGHTENS a gate): `segmentInvokesComplete` (`internal/hook/precomplete.go:366-394`) strips only leading env-assignments (`isEnvAssignment`) and `cd`/`pushd` prefixes before checking `fields[0]` is the mindspec binary and `fields[1] == \"complete\"`. Unquoted wrapper commands therefore fail OPEN: `env VAR=x mindspec complete …`, `timeout 30 mindspec complete …`, `xargs … mindspec complete`, and `command mindspec complete …` are not recognized as invoking complete, so the pre-complete gate does not fire. Change: extend the matcher to recognize and skip the catchable unquoted wrapper prefixes (`env`, `timeout`, `xargs`, `command`) so the wrapped `mindspec complete` is still detected. The matcher's terminal check is PRESERVED unchanged — after stripping wrapper prefixes it still requires `isMindspecBinary(fields[0]) \u0026\u0026 fields[1] == \"complete\"`, so the tightening fires ONLY when `complete` is genuinely the wrapped command and introduces no false positives (`timeout 30 go test` strips to `go test` → not mindspec → false; `env FOO=bar mindspec next` → `fields[1] != \"complete\"` → false). The exact per-wrapper arg-skip rules (`timeout`: skip the duration plus its `-s SIG`/`--preserve-status`/`-k` flags; `command`: skip `-p`/`-v`/`-V`; `xargs`: skip its flags; bare `env`: skip leading `VAR=x` assignments after the keyword) are a plan-phase implementation detail to enumerate precisely so the matcher neither under-skips (misses the wrapped complete) nor over-skips into a wrong `fields[0]`. The QUOTED `sh -c '…'` / `eval '…'` forms are structurally unreachable by a non-executing tokenizer and remain an explicitly-documented accepted ADR-0037 residual — do NOT attempt to match them; document that boundary in code/comment. **What must be true after:** `env VAR=x mindspec complete`, `timeout 30 mindspec complete`, `xargs … mindspec complete`, and `command mindspec complete` are all detected by `segmentInvokesComplete` and trigger the pre-complete gate; the quoted `sh -c`/`eval` forms remain a documented residual.\n\n5. **(pi24 — S) Make the harness merge-to-main assertion direction-aware and fix its message.** Failure mode today (test-layer only): `preApproveImplMainMergeOrPRViolation` (`internal/harness/asserts.go`, the merge check around lines 199-207) flags any `git merge` whose args contain both `merge` and `main` as a pre-approve \"merge-to-main occurred before approve impl\" violation, regardless of DIRECTION. This is direction-blind: `git merge main` (merging main INTO a feature/spec branch — a legitimate update) matches the same as the genuinely-bad `git merge \u003cbranch\u003e` while on `main`, and the message (\"merge-to-main occurred\") is misleading for the safe direction. (The agent-facing root cause was already fixed in commit `d5d8ee54` / `implement.md:98`; this is the residual test-layer defect.) Change: make the assertion direction-aware — only flag the genuinely-bad direction (a merge that lands content ONTO `main`, i.e. run while the checkout is on `main` / `git merge \u003cspec-branch\u003e` into main), allowing `git merge main` into another branch — and correct the violation message to describe the actual bad direction. **What must be true after:** the assertion flags only merges that land onto `main` before approve-impl (with an accurate message) and no longer flags a legitimate `git merge main` into a feature/spec branch.\n\n## ADR Decisions\n\nCited by ID — full text under `.mindspec/docs/adr/`:\n\n- see ADR-0035 — Agent Error Contract — Recovery Lines and Exit Codes\n- see ADR-0037 — Panel Gate as Enforced Contract — panel.json Convention, Thresholds, and the Trust Boundary\n- see ADR-0036 — Ownership Discovery — Zero Framework Cognition for OWNERSHIP.yaml and source_globs\n- see ADR-0012 — Compose with External CLIs, Don't Wrap Them","acceptance_criteria":"- [ ] `segmentInvokesComplete` returns true for `env VAR=x mindspec complete`,\n`timeout 30 mindspec complete`, `xargs … mindspec complete`, and `command mindspec complete`;\n`timeout 30 go test` and `env FOO=bar mindspec next` are NOT caught; the quoted `sh -c`/`eval`\nresidual is documented. Table-driven tests cover the wrapper prefixes. RED-on-revert.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","assignee":"mrmaxsteel","owner":"richardmaxsteel@gmail.com","created_at":"2026-06-13T22:28:00Z","created_by":"mrmaxsteel","updated_at":"2026-06-14T06:57:51Z","started_at":"2026-06-14T06:51:24Z","closed_at":"2026-06-14T06:57:51Z","close_reason":"2u0u; manual","metadata":{"spec_id":"098-lifecycle-correctness-2","file_paths":null,"mindspec_doc_skew_at":"2026-06-14T06:57:22Z","mindspec_doc_skew_by":"richardmaxsteel@gmail.com","mindspec_doc_skew_reason":"Pre-complete gate hardening (R4/7eup): extend segmentInvokesComplete to strip unquoted env/timeout/xargs/command wrappers before the terminal isMindspecBinary+'complete' check, so wrapper-prefixed 'mindspec complete' is no longer fail-open; quoted sh -c/eval remain a documented ADR-0037 residual. Internal/hook (workflow, ADR-0037) change; verify APPROVE (no false-positives, no off-by-one)."},"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"mindspec-dn4h.4","depends_on_id":"mindspec-dn4h","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-06-13T23:28:00Z","created_by":"mrmaxsteel","metadata":"{}"}],"dependency_count":0,"dependent_count":0,"comment_count":0}
 {"_type":"issue","id":"mindspec-dn4h.3","title":"[098-lifecycle-correctness-2] Bead 3: Auto-fill plan `version` to `\"1\"` when absent (R3 / e6qq)","description":"`internal/validate/plan.go:304` (`checkFrontmatterFields`) raises a HARD error\n`frontmatter-version: missing required field: version` when `fm.Version == \"\"`, even though sibling\nchecks were already relaxed for ZFC alignment (`StepsCount \u003c 3` demoted to a warning; empty\n`adr_citations` demoted when `## ADR Fitness` is present). Nothing downstream reads\n`PlanFrontmatter.Version` (the only consumers, `internal/approve/plan.go` and\n`internal/validate/divergence.go`, read `ADRCitations`/`WorkChunks` only), so any well-defined\ndefault is safe. This requirement LOOSENS the gate: when `fm.Version == \"\"`, AUTO-FILL it to the\ncanonical default value `\"1\"` (the string `\"1\"`) instead of erroring. `status`/`spec_id` stay\nhard-required. Independent of all other beads (single-file). (S.)\n\n**Steps**\n1. In `checkFrontmatterFields` (`internal/validate/plan.go` ~301-307), replace the\n   `if fm.Version == \"\" { r.AddError(\"frontmatter-version\", …) }` branch with an auto-fill:\n   `if fm.Version == \"\" { fm.Version = \"1\" }` (mutating the parsed `*PlanFrontmatter` so the\n   defaulted value is exactly the string `\"1\"`). Leave the `Status`/`SpecID` hard errors UNCHANGED.\n2. Confirm the auto-fill propagates to any consumer that reads `fm.Version` AFTER validation (the\n   pointer mutation makes the defaulted value visible); since no current consumer reads `Version`,\n   the only observable effect is that the plan no longer hard-errors on `frontmatter-version`.\n3. Add a unit test in `internal/validate/`: a plan missing ONLY `version` (all other required\n   frontmatter present) (a) no longer produces a `frontmatter-version` error and (b) has its\n   `version` defaulted to exactly `\"1\"`; assert a plan missing `status` or `spec_id` STILL hard-errors.\n4. UPDATE the existing `TestValidatePlan_Mi